          <div class="breadcrumb"><a href="/">Home</a></div>                              <h2>Working Man, Society Bride</h2>                                                  <div class="clear-block">
            <div id="node-13" class="node">



  
  <div class="content clear-block">
    <p>&nbsp;</p>
<div><img hspace="10" vspace="10" align="left" src="/sites/default/files/Working%20man%2C%20web.jpg" width="196" height="320" />Mills &amp; Boon</div>
<div>Hardback March 2007 ISBN 978 0&nbsp;263 19755 6</div>
<div>Paperback May&nbsp;2007 ISBN 978 0 263 85173&nbsp;1</div>
<div>&nbsp;</div>
<div><em>He was a most impressive&nbsp;man&nbsp;</em></div>
<div>&nbsp;</div>
<div>Well over six feet tall, with broad, broad shoulders, he was the most good-looking man Lady Lucinda Vernley had ever seen - and the most insufferably rude! With her family expecting her to make a good marriage according to her station, how could she possibly be fantasising about a man she had seen working on&nbsp;her father's estate?&nbsp; It was tempting, though, to dream of a world where there were no social boundaries or rules.</div>
<div>&nbsp;</div>
<div>Myles Moorcroft didn't dress the gentleman, but by his manner there was something about him&nbsp;that had Lucy well and truly attracted and intrigued.&nbsp;&nbsp;</div>
<div>&nbsp;</div>
<div>&nbsp;</div>
<div><img hspace="10" vspace="10" align="left" src="http://www.marynichols.co.uk/sites/default/files/Working%20Man%2C%20Society%20Bride_0.jpg" width="100" height="158" />Harlequin Historical</div>
<div>Paperback Sept 2008</div>
<div>ISBN 978 0 373 30553 2</div>
<div>North American edition.&nbsp;&nbsp;</div>
<div>Also available as an ebook.&nbsp;</div>
<div>&nbsp;</div>
<p>&nbsp;</p>  </div>

